{"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language"]]},"kind":"article","schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language\/AboutTheLanguageReference"},"metadata":{"title":"About the Language Reference"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Read the notation that the formal grammar uses."}],"sections":[],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"This part of the book describes the formal grammar of the Swift programming language.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"The grammar described here is intended to help you understand the language in more"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"detail, rather than to allow you to directly implement a parser or compiler.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Swift language is relatively small, because many common types, functions, and operators"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"that appear virtually everywhere in Swift code","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"are actually defined in the Swift standard library. Although these types, functions,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and operators aren’t part of the Swift language itself,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"they’re used extensively in the discussions and code examples in this part of the book."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"How-to-Read-the-Grammar","text":"How to Read the Grammar","type":"heading","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The notation used to describe the formal grammar of the Swift programming language"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"follows a few conventions:"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"An arrow (→) is used to mark grammar productions and can be read as “can consist of.”","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Syntactic categories are indicated by ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"italic"}]},{"type":"text","text":" text and appear on both sides"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of a grammar production rule.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Literal words and punctuation are indicated by "},{"inlineContent":[{"code":"boldface constant width","type":"codeVoice"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and appear only on the right-hand side of a grammar production rule."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Alternative grammar productions are separated by vertical","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"bars (|). When alternative productions are too long to read easily,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"they’re broken into multiple grammar production rules on new lines.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In a few cases, regular font text is used to describe the right-hand side"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"of a grammar production rule."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Optional syntactic categories and literals are marked by a trailing","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"question mark, ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"?","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As an example, the grammar of a getter-setter block is defined as follows:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"t